  "prompt": "English Grammar: Is it 'Can you explain me?' or 'Could you explain me?'",
  "response": "In English grammar, neither \"Can you explain me?\" nor \"Could you explain me?\" is correct when asking someone to explain something to you. The correct preposition to use in this context is \"to,\" not \"me\" directly after \"explain.\"\n\nThe correct ways to ask someone to explain something would be:\n\n- \"Can you explain it to me?\" (using \"can\" for a more direct or informal request)\n- \"Could you explain it to me?\" (using \"could\" for a more polite or formal request)\n\nBoth of these sentences are grammatically correct and commonly used, with \"Could you explain it to me?\" being the more polite option.",
